  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad and global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make it appear legitimate. This practice is universally condemned and criminalized because it facilitates organized crime, corruption, terrorism, and other illegal activities.\n\n### Key Points on the Legal Consensus:\n1. **International Agreements**:\n   - The **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** was one of the first international treaties to criminalize money laundering.\n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental organization founded in 1989, has established global standards (the FATF Recommendations) to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to implementing these standards.\n\n2. **National Laws**:\n   - Virtually every country has enacted laws specifically targeting money laundering. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and the **Patriot Act (2001)** provide the legal framework for combating money laundering.\n     - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** harmonize laws across member states.\n     - Countries like the **United Kingdom**, **Canada**, **Australia**, and others have similarly robust legislation.\n\n3. **Penalties**:\n   - Penalties for money laundering are severe and can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences. For example, in the U.S., individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to 20 years in prison and fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds.\n\n4. **Global Cooperation**:\n   - Countries and financial institutions are required to cooperate in efforts to detect and prevent money laundering. This includes reporting suspicious transactions, sharing information across borders, and freezing or seizing illicit assets.\n\n### Exceptions and Challenges:\nWhile the consensus against money laundering is nearly universal, enforcement and effectiveness vary across jurisdictions. Some countries may have weaker regulatory frameworks or may be exploited as havens for illicit financial activities. However, international pressure and cooperation continue to strengthen global efforts to combat this crime.\n\nIn summary, there is no debate on whether money laundering is illegal\u2014it is unequivocally against the law in nearly every country, with robust legal frameworks and international cooperation in place to address it.",
